"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47230","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-04-10","<p>The Table below details the companies used and the total amounts paid to them in the last financial year. We are unable to identify separately the amounts retained by the companies as fees and the amounts passed on to the temporary worker by the company.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Agency</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong>£k</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Adecco UK Ltd</p></td><td><p>1,162</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Michael Page International Recruitment Ltd</p></td><td><p>533</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Methods Consulting Ltd</p></td><td><p>517</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Parity Resources Ltd</p></td><td><p>461</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Allen Lane Ltd</p></td><td><p>406</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47230/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-10T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47230/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47230/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-04-07","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, which five companies were used most often to provide temporary workers for his Department in the last financial year; and how much in agency fees was paid to each of them.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","195551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47231","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-04-10","<p>All households will benefit from our changes. Whilst the reduction in individual household bills will depend on the energy supplier, this package, including VAT, will be worth an average of around £50 to households, compared to what would have happened without these changes. All customers on fixed tariffs will receive the £12 rebate from suppliers in autumn and the vast majority of them can either switch to a new tariff created since the Autumn Statement without any charge or will be switching to a new tariff anyway as a result of their fixed contract coming to an end this year.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47231/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-10T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47231/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47231/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-04-07","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps he is taking to ensure that all customers receive the full benefit of reductions in levies on energy bills.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","195520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47232","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-04-10","<p> </p><p>The figures are as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>(a)</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Average Defra spend per head on flood and coastal erosion risk management in England (£)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005/06</p></td><td><p>9.51</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006/07</p></td><td><p>9.47</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007/08</p></td><td><p>9.34</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/09</p></td><td><p>10.61</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>11.83</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>12.53</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>10.71</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>10.77</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>11.34</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>14.86</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>The figures for each year is the total Defra spend on flood and coastal erosion risk management divided by the most recent ONS population estimate for mid-2012</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>· Figures before 2005/06 are not available in a comparable format.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>· Figures for 2013/14 and 2014/15 are budget allocations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>· Figures for 2015/16 are not available as the budget has not yet been set.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>(b)</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Flood management in Wales is a devolved matter and Defra has made no estimate of the amount spent per person.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47232/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-10T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47232/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47232/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-04-07","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate he has made of the amount spent per person on flood defences in (a) England and (b) Wales in each year since 2001 to date; and what estimate he has made of the amounts in each year to 2016.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","195489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47233","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-04-28","<p> </p><p>Policy on national parks and planning are devolved matters. For Wales, they are a matter for the Welsh Assembly Government. National parks and areas of outstanding natural beauty are given the strongest protection from damaging development through the National Planning Policy Framework.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Defra works closely with the Department for Communities and Local Government to ensure planning policies take account of the special character of England's protected landscapes. For example, as made clear on 6 March by the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, Nick Boles, the extended permitted development rights for conversion of agricultural buildings to a dwelling house will not apply in national parks or areas of outstanding natural beauty (6 Mar 2014, <em>Official Report</em>, column 50WS).</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47233/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-28T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47233/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47233/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-04-07","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to deter inappropriate development in National Parks in England and Wales; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","195595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47234","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-04-11","<p> </p><p>This table sets out the information requested in respect of 2012-13, the last financial year for which audited information is available. Information relating to 2013-14 will be available in July 2014, once the Department's accounts for the year have been audited and published. The figures relate to the Core Department.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Consultancy firm</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Amount paid</strong></p><p><strong>in 2012-13 (£)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ernst and Young</p></td><td><p>1,012,378</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Freshfields Bruckhaus Deringer</p></td><td><p>587,922</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Local Partnerships</p></td><td><p>152,226</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>KPMG</p></td><td><p>118,351</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bureau Veritas UK Ltd.</p></td><td><p>105,185</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Baker Tilly</p></td><td><p>101,925</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>ADAS UK Ltd.</p></td><td><p>99,138</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GHK Consulting Ltd.</p></td><td><p>71,424</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Resource Decisions Ltd.</p></td><td><p>64,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Temple Group Ltd.</p></td><td><p>44,380</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47234/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-11T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47234/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47234/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-04-07","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, which 10 consultancy firms were paid the most by his Department in the last financial year; and how much each of those firms was paid.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","195574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47235","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-04-10","<p> </p><p>Defra has received a copy of the report on the findings of the Epilobee Study and is considering its content.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We take the issue of honeybee health seriously. We have a long-established bee health programme, which includes inspection of colonies, diagnosis of bee pests and diseases, and training for beekeepers. Bee health forms a key part of the National Pollinator Strategy, which is currently out for consultation.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47235/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-10T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47235/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47235/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-04-07","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will make an assessment of the implications for his policy of the findings of the European Commission's Epilobee Study, published on 2 April 2014; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","195673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47236","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-04-24","<p> </p><p>Since May 2010, 202 core Defra staff have transferred to the private sector.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47236/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-24T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47236/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47236/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-04-07","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many jobs have been transferred from the public to the private sector as a result of privatisations or outsourcing by his Department since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","195510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47237","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-04-10","<p> </p><p>Pesticides are authorised for sale and use only if effects on non-target species, including honeybees, are not unacceptable.</p><p>The Government has, over a number of years, commissioned broader research on the effects of pesticides on honeybees. Details of all Defra research can be found at <a href="http://randd.defra.gov.uk/" target="_blank">http://randd.defra.gov.uk/</a></p><p>Current Defra research projects include:</p><ul><li>· PS2370 <em>Interpretation of pesticide residues in honeybees</em></li><li>· PS2374 <em>Radio Frequency Identification (RFID) of the effects of pesticides on foraging bees</em></li><li>· PS2376 <em>Evaluation of procedures to improve estimates of exposure of pollinators to neonicotinoid insecticides</em></li></ul><p>In addition, one of the nine projects being carried out under the Insect Pollinators Initiative (which is part-funded by Defra) is <em>An investigation into the synergistic impact of sub-lethal exposure to industrial chemicals on the learning capacity and performance of bees</em>.</p><p>Research needs in this area are kept under active consideration.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47237/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-10T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47237/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47237/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-04-07","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what studies the Government has (a) conducted and (b) commissioned on the effects of pesticides on honeybee mortality.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","195674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47238","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-04-28","<p> </p><p>Recent steps taken by Defra to protect the UK's honeybee population include the launch of the National Pollinator Strategy and conducting a 12 month policy review, in collaboration with stakeholders, on the pests and diseases affecting honeybees. Longer term initiatives include the Healthy Bees Plan and continued funding of the National Bee Unit.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47238/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-28T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47238/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47238/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-04-07","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent steps the Government has taken to protect the UK's honeybee population.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","195672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47239","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-04-15","<p> </p><p>No estimate has been made of the number of people owning dogs who have previously been banned. However, the table shows the number of people convicted of breaching disqualification orders, in respect of keeping any animal, made under the Animal Welfare Act 2006.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Convictions</p></td><td><p>43</p></td><td><p>59</p></td><td><p>73</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong>Source:</strong> Data provided by the Home Office on 9 April 2014.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47239/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-15T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47239/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47239/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-04-07","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent estimate he has made of the number of dogs owned by people who have previously been banned from owning dogs.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","195407"
