"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47058","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-04-10","<p>I am concerned by reports of excessive use of force in protests, and reports of armed groups using violence. I condemn all acts of violence and call on all sides to show restraint. It is important that the Venezuelan government respects the right to protest peacefully and ensures public security. The Government has called for all sides to take steps to avoid confrontation, reduce tensions and to create the right conditions for genuine dialogue to take place.</p><p>My right hon. Friend the Member for East Devon (Hugo Swire MP) has written to the Venezuelan government emphasising the importance of respecting peaceful protest and the importance of dialogue to take place between the parties. He has offered the UK's assistance in the reconciliation process and asked to speak to his Venezuelan opposite number. The British Embassy in Caracas urges peaceful dialogue through its contacts with a range of actors in Venezuelan society.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Mr William Hague","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47058/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-10T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47058/answer","Biography information for Lord Hague of Richmond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47058/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-04-04","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Venezuelan counterpart on exercising restraint in response to protests in that country.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Alexander","Paisley and Renfrewshire South","Mr Douglas Alexander","195311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47059","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-04-09","<p>I refer my honourable friend to the statement I made to the House on 8 April 2014, Offical Report, column 101. We are gravely concerned about the situation in Crimea and in the east of Ukraine where armed groups have seized government buildings in Donetsk, Kharkiv and Lugansk. There can be no justification for this action, which bears all the hallmarks of a Russian strategy to destabilise Ukraine. Russia should be clear that the deliberate escalation of this crisis will bring serious political and economic consequences.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Mr William Hague","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47059/answer",,,,,"195329","2014-04-09T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47059/answer","Biography information for Lord Hague of Richmond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47059/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-04-04","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the security situation in Ukraine.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Alexander","Paisley and Renfrewshire South","Mr Douglas Alexander","195312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47060","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-04-10","<p>The UK has pledged £10m in assistance to Ukraine from the Department for International Development bilateral programme. The Secretary of State for International Development, my right hon. Friend the Member for Putney (Justine Greening) will keep this allocation under review. The UK also provides support to Ukraine through our core contributions to the EU, the World Bank, the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, the International Monetary Fund and the UN.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Mr William Hague","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47060/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-10T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47060/answer","Biography information for Lord Hague of Richmond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47060/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-04-04","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he plans to increase the UK's bilateral financial support for Ukraine in the next six months.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Alexander","Paisley and Renfrewshire South","Mr Douglas Alexander","195313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47061","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-04-10","<p>There are no current plans for the Minister of State, my right hon. Friend the Member for East Devon (Mr Swire) to visit Sri Lanka. We continue to engage regularly with the Sri Lankan government at Ministerial and official level on a wide range of issues.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Mr William Hague","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47061/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-10T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47061/answer","Biography information for Lord Hague of Richmond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47061/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-04-04","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when the Minister of State, the hon. Member for East Devon, will next travel to Sri Lanka.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Alexander","Paisley and Renfrewshire South","Mr Douglas Alexander","195359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47062","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-04-09","<p>I refer my honourable friend to the statement I made to the House on 8 April 2014, Offical Report, column 101. We are gravely concerned about the situation in Crimea and in the east of Ukraine where armed groups have seized government buildings in Donetsk, Kharkiv and Lugansk. There can be no justification for this action, which bears all the hallmarks of a Russian strategy to destabilise Ukraine. Russia should be clear that the deliberate escalation of this crisis will bring serious political and economic consequences.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Mr William Hague","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47062/answer",,,,,"195312","2014-04-09T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47062/answer","Biography information for Lord Hague of Richmond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47062/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-04-04","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the likelihood of a further Russian military incursion into eastern Ukraine.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Alexander","Paisley and Renfrewshire South","Mr Douglas Alexander","195329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47063","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-04-09","<p>We welcomed the recent consensus adoption at the Human Rights Council of both the European Union's regular resolution on ‘freedom of religion or belief' and the Organisation of the Islamic Conference's resolution on ‘religious intolerance'. This gives the international community a valuable starting point on which to base discussions on how best to implement these resolutions in practice. <br><br>Senior Minister of State, my noble Friend the right hon. Baroness Warsi, is leading an international initiative to build up greater political support for practical measures to combat religious intolerance and promote the social and economic benefits of religious pluralism.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Mr William Hague","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47063/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-09T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47063/answer","Biography information for Lord Hague of Richmond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47063/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-04-04","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what action the Government is recommending on the UN Human Rights Council to tackle the persecution of Christians around the world.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Alexander","Paisley and Renfrewshire South","Mr Douglas Alexander","195330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47064","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-04-09","<p>The British Government has regular dialogue with the Moroccan authorities, including on Western Sahara. We encourage concrete progress towards improving human rights in Western Sahara, including effective human rights monitoring. I discussed this most recently during my visit to Rabat in March.</p>","Faversham and Mid Kent","Hugh Robertson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47064/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-09T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47064/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugh Robertson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47064/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-04-04","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what his policy is on human rights monitoring in Western Sahara.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","195319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47065","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-04-09","<p>Invitations to the 2014 Commonwealth Games in Glasgow are issued by the Commonwealth Games Association of each participating nation. <br><br>The Minister of State, my right hon. Friend the Member for East Devon (Mr Swire) discussed attendance at the Commonwealth Games and other games related matters during his meeting with the Commonwealth Secretary-General on 19 March.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Mr William Hague","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47065/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-09T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47065/answer","Biography information for Lord Hague of Richmond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47065/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-04-04","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what advice his Department has given to the Commonwealth (a) Secretariat and (b) Chairperson on the attendance of President Rajapaksa at the Glasgow Commonwealth Games.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Alexander","Paisley and Renfrewshire South","Mr Douglas Alexander","195331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47066","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-04-09","<p>We read the 2013 World Report from Human Rights Watch and the 2013 United Nations Secretary-General's annual report with interest. We regularly discuss with Morocco the importance of full respect for human rights in Western Sahara, including in discussions at the UN Security Council, and during my visit to Rabat in March. However, we also welcome the facilitation by the government of Morocco of access to the Territory for United Nations special procedures mandate holders. I recently made a statement warmly welcoming the government of Morocco's announcement that the process to ratify the OPCAT will be completed imminently. I also welcomed Morocco's new commitments to investigate complaints of human rights violations made to the National Council of Human Rights within a fixed 3 month deadline, and the definitive ending of Military Tribunal trials for civilians.</p>","Faversham and Mid Kent","Hugh Robertson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47066/answer",,,,,"195375","2014-04-09T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47066/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugh Robertson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47066/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-04-04","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the conclusions of the 2013 World Report by Human Rights Watch regarding Morocco's 2011 constitution and human rights.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","195394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47067","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-04-09","<p>We read the 2013 World Report from Human Rights Watch and the 2013 United Nations Secretary-General's annual report with interest. We regularly discuss with Morocco the importance of full respect for human rights in Western Sahara, including in discussions at the UN Security Council, and during my visit to Rabat in March. However, we also welcome the facilitation by the government of Morocco of access to the Territory for United Nations special procedures mandate holders. I recently made a statement warmly welcoming the government of Morocco's announcement that the process to ratify the OPCAT will be completed imminently. I also welcomed Morocco's new commitments to investigate complaints of human rights violations made to the National Council of Human Rights within a fixed 3 month deadline, and the definitive ending of Military Tribunal trials for civilians.</p>","Faversham and Mid Kent","Hugh Robertson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47067/answer",,,,,"195394","2014-04-09T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47067/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugh Robertson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47067/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-04-04","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the statement of the UN Secretary General in his report S/2013/220 published in April 2013 on the human rights situation in Western Sahara; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","195375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47068","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-04-10","<p>During the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Richmond's (Yorks) (Mr Hague) meeting with Egyptian Foreign Minister Nabil Fahmy on 2 April, he discussed the political situation in Egypt, including the Presidential elections scheduled for 26-27 May. The Foreign Secretary raised his strong concern over the death sentence imposed on 529 people on 24 March and the case of two British journalists who have been charged in Egypt and are currently being tried in absentia. He asked the Egyptian Government to review these issues as a matter of urgency and to ensure that the individuals' human and legal rights are properly upheld.</p><p>The Foreign Secretary condemned the terrorist attacks of 2 April in Cairo and sent his condolences to the family of the victim and those who had been injured. He reiterated the importance of cooperation against the shared threat from terrorism. He also raised the UK's concerns regarding the security situation in the South Sinai region. He urged the Egyptian Government to do all it could to protect British nationals in Egypt, including those visiting the Red Sea resorts over the holiday season, and to take further measures against the risk of terrorism.</p><p>The two ministers also discussed recent events in the Middle East, including the crisis in Syria and the importance of progress on the Middle East Peace Process.</p><p>There has been no date set for their next meeting.</p>","Faversham and Mid Kent","Hugh Robertson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47068/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-10T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47068/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugh Robertson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47068/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-04-04","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the outcome was of his meeting with his Egyptian counterpart on 2 April 2014; and when the next meeting is planned.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","195383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47069","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-04-28","<p>As I made clear to the House in the adjournment debate on this subject on 2 April, combating violence and discrimination against LGBT communities forms an integral part of our tireless efforts to protect and promote human rights internationally. We have raised our deep concern about the Anti-Homosexuality Act with the Government of Uganda at the highest levels. Since that debate, the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my hon. Friend the Member for Boston and Skegness (Mr Simmonds) has raised the issue with the Ugandan Foreign Minister on 3 April.</p><p>Uganda's Anti-Homosexuality Act runs counter to the Commonwealth's commitment to equality and respect without discrimination on any grounds. The Foreign Secretary wrote to the Secretary General of the Commonwealth on 1 March to ask him to work with us to review the worrying trend on lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender rights in some Commonwealth member states. I discussed the issue with the Commonwealth Secretary-General on 19 March. We also use Commonwealth fora, such as the Commonwealth Law Ministers' meetings (CLMM), to raise concerns. Our High Commission in Kampala continues to discuss the issue with Commonwealth High Commissions.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47069/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-28T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47069/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47069/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-04-04","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterparts in Commonwealth governments regarding Uganda's Anti-Homosexuality Act.","false","Biography information for Naomi Long","Belfast East","Naomi Long","195354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47070","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-04-09","We have consistently raised our concerns about the Anti-Homosexuality Act with the Ugandan Government at all levels. I most recently discussed the legislation with the Ugandan High Commissioner to the UK on 18 March.","Boston and Skegness","Mark Simmonds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47070/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-09T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47070/answer","Biography information for Mark Simmonds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47070/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-04-04","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he or officials in his Department have had with the High Commissioner of Uganda regarding Uganda's Anti-Homosexuality Act.","false","Biography information for Naomi Long","Belfast East","Naomi Long","195406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47088","Home Office","false","2014-04-10","<p> </p><p>The number of civil penalties imposed on hauliers under the Immigration and Asylum Act 1999 in each year since 2010 is as follows;<br><br>2010/11 814<br>2011/12 648<br>2012/13 915<br><br>The 2013/14 figure cannot be provided as penalties for this period will continue to be imposed as the process of evidence gathering and recommendations continue.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47088/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-10T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47088/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47088/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47088/answer/previousversion/5382","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-04-04","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many civil penalties were imposed on hauliers under the Immigration and Asylum Act 1999 in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","195392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47089","Home Office","false","2014-04-30","<p>The Government consulted publicly on whether licensing hours should be relaxed during the FIFA World Cup 2014. A range of representations were made both for and against the proposal. We received a total of 1,468 responses to the online consultation. 77% (1,095 respondents) believed that any national relaxation of licensing hours should apply to England and Wales. However, only 2% (25 respondents) identified themselves as living or working in Wales. <br><br>While a majority of Welsh respondents favoured a relaxation for England and Wales, there was a difference between English and Welsh respondents about how the relaxation might be delivered. There was a clear majority of Welsh respondents who favoured using the Temporary Event Notice system, rather than a blanket relaxation, while of English respondents the majority (74%) favoured a blanket relaxation. This is consistent with what the Government has opted to do: a national blanket relaxation in England, with licensed premises able to use the Temporary Event Notice system in Wales.<br><br>Section 172 of the Licensing Act 2003 allows the relevant Secretary of State to make an order relaxing opening hours for licensed premises to mark occasions of ‘exceptional international, national or local significance'. The Government considers that the England football team's participation in the FIFA World Cup 2014 is an event of exceptional national significance in England. <br><br>The Government has therefore decided not to include Wales in the relaxation of licensing hours for the FIFA World Cup 2014. However, licensed premises in Wales wishing to remain open beyond their licensed hours will be able to do so by using the Temporary Event Notice procedure.</p><p> </p>","Lewes","Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47089/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-30T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47089/answer","Biography information for Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47089/answer","Lewes","Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47089/answer/previousversion/5664","Biography information for Norman Baker","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-04-04","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, for what reasons premises in Wales have not been included in the extension of licensing hours during the FIFA World Cup.","false","Biography information for Alun Cairns","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns","195384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47090","Home Office","false","2014-04-10","<p> </p><p>The Home Office does not hold this information centrally.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47090/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-10T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47090/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47090/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/47090/answer/previousversion/5378","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-04-04","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many vehicles were impounded under the Immigration and Asylum Act 1999 in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","195391"
